00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:01.950
to that.

00:02:01.950 --> 00:02:04.760
But that's not what we're
going to talk about today.

00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:07.540
What we're going to talk
about is another very big area

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:09.990
called pricing, which
is pricing and hedging

00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:11.600
of complex instruments.

00:02:11.600 --> 00:02:18.350
And that area is really
about essentially

00:02:18.350 --> 00:02:21.430
when you have a complex
product that you don't really

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:25.410
know the price of, but you know
the prices of other products.

00:02:25.410 --> 00:02:27.710
And then you can use
the other products

00:02:27.710 --> 00:02:32.290
to essentially replicate the
payoff of your complex product.

00:02:32.290 --> 00:02:35.660
Then you can use
mathematical techniques

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:39.260
to essentially say, look,
the main statement is hey,

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:41.780
because I can
replicate my payoff,

00:02:41.780 --> 00:02:45.850
and using products that
I know the price of,

00:02:45.850 --> 00:02:49.640
then that means that
I can say something

00:02:49.640 --> 00:02:51.890
about the price of
my complex product.

00:02:51.890 --> 00:02:53.860
I can basically price it.

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:55.830
And not only can
I price it, but I

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:58.710
can also-- when I
give the price, I

00:02:58.710 --> 00:03:02.770
know that I can eliminate
any uncertainty from owning

00:03:02.770 --> 00:03:05.510
the product by executing
a hedging replication

00:03:05.510 --> 00:03:08.465
strategy-- at least
theoretically speaking.

00:03:11.070 --> 00:03:14.200
So that's the area we're
going to focus today.

00:03:14.200 --> 00:03:21.600
And our main focus is going to
be on FX-- foreign exchange--

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:23.880
interest rates, and
credit-- and in particular

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:26.920
about credit-FX hybrid models.

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:30.420
We're going to be talking
about essentially what

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:33.350
happens, why do we need
credit-FX hybrid models,

00:03:33.350 --> 00:03:37.530
and going through an
example of a simple one,

00:03:37.530 --> 00:03:39.629
and how to apply it.

00:03:39.629 --> 00:03:42.170
In particular-- and there's the
mathematical techniques we're

00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:44.489
going to be using--
as I said, we

00:03:44.489 --> 00:03:47.030
are going to be talking about
the risk-neutral pricing, which

00:03:47.030 --> 00:03:49.220
is essentially replication.

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:54.350
And we're going to talk about
how to use jump processes--

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:57.100
which you might have seen in
other parts of your studies

00:03:57.100 --> 00:04:02.872
as Poisson processes-- to
describe certain behaviors

00:04:02.872 --> 00:04:05.880
of price behavior that you
cannot really describe very

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:08.990
easily using pure diffusion
Brownian motions that you

00:04:08.990 --> 00:04:13.250
probably have seen
so far in the course.

00:04:13.250 --> 00:04:14.624
And why do we care about that?

00:04:14.624 --> 00:04:16.540
Well, there are certain
financial applications

00:04:16.540 --> 00:04:17.540
where this is important.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:20.300
And in particular,
something that

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:24.150
happened in the last few years--
the sovereign crisis in Europe.

00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:26.259
And also, it has happen
not just last year.

00:04:26.259 --> 00:04:28.550
This happened many times in
other parts of the emerging

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:29.170
markets.

00:04:29.170 --> 00:04:31.570
And given the emerging
markets as my background,

00:04:31.570 --> 00:04:34.210
I've worked on these
kind of models.

00:04:34.210 --> 00:04:38.550
And this is, when you
have Greek bonds in Euros,

00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:42.940
and there's a potential for
