00:05:26.790 --> 00:05:28.510
But in other emerging
markets in history,

00:05:28.510 --> 00:05:30.650
it has happened before.

00:05:30.650 --> 00:05:33.980
So it's not really
an empty question.

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:39.090
So foreign exchange-- how do
we describe it in math finance?

00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:40.480
Well, we think of
it as the price

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:43.570
of a unit of foreign
currency in dollars.

00:05:43.570 --> 00:05:46.870
In our presentation we're
going to denote the spot FX

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:49.830
rate, which is the current
rate of exchange, by S.

00:05:49.830 --> 00:05:54.020
And here is a sample graph
of euro-USD FX rates.

00:05:54.020 --> 00:05:56.740
You can see it looks
like a random walk.

00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:59.300
It's very well described
in normal circumstances

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:00.000
as random walk.

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:09.280
So one very fundamental property
that connects FX and interest

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:13.880
rates is the so-called
FX forwards interest rate

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:19.700
parity, which says if I have
a certain amount of money--

00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:27.710
in this example, $5 million,
and I can invest it,

00:06:27.710 --> 00:06:30.200
there's two ways I can
utilize this money.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:33.360
One way is to just
invest it at a dollar

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:34.620
kind of risk-free rate.

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:37.700
And we're assuming here
we have a risk-free rate--

00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:39.150
the standard assumption.

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:41.460
Or we can do something
like we can take the money,

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:44.112
exchange it into,
say, euros, invest

00:06:44.112 --> 00:06:46.620
it using the euro
risk-free rate,

00:06:46.620 --> 00:06:50.720
and then exchange it
back into dollars.

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:56.640
And this is essentially used
to price FX forward contracts.

00:06:56.640 --> 00:06:59.890
So FX forward contracts
are a contract

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:02.410
that allow you to say, look,
I'm going to agree with you,

00:07:02.410 --> 00:07:06.850
then in one month's time,
I'm going to, say, give you

00:07:06.850 --> 00:07:11.110
4,108,405 euros, and you're
going to give me back

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:15.960
$5,170,000.

00:07:15.960 --> 00:07:18.839
It's essentially an agreement;
it's a derivative contract.

00:07:18.839 --> 00:07:21.130
And if you see the-- if you
have this forward contract,

00:07:21.130 --> 00:07:24.070
you can lock in, essentially,
through conversion in euros.

00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:26.670
So you can lock in an
effective dollar interest rate.

00:07:26.670 --> 00:07:32.060
So FX forwards can be
essentially described fully

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:34.700
by knowing the interest rates
in each currency and the spot FX

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:36.160
rate.

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:39.220
Conversely, you can infer
foreign interest rates

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:42.790
knowing the FX forwards.

00:07:42.790 --> 00:07:43.780
They're very connected.

00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:48.620
Yes?

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:50.070
AUDIENCE: In this example,
there's no mispricing,

00:07:50.070 --> 00:07:51.236
so you get that same amount.

00:07:51.236 --> 00:07:52.257
Is that the idea?

00:07:52.257 --> 00:07:54.590
STEFAN ANDREEV: In this
example, there is no mispricing.

00:07:54.590 --> 00:07:56.230
You get back the same amount.

00:07:56.230 --> 00:07:59.790
So we are assuming, essentially,
there's no arbitrage.

00:07:59.790 --> 00:08:01.680
We're not assuming,
but we're given--

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:04.880
if the prices were, indeed,
if this interest rate-- 4.6%

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:09.090
in Euros-- interest rate was
4.6, in dollars it's 3.4.

00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:12.200
And here are the current spots,
which is 127 and the forward,

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:16.790
125-- if these were, in
fact, the observable mark

00:08:16.790 --> 00:08:20.460
quantities in the market, then
there would be no arbitrage.

00:08:20.460 --> 00:08:23.640
And there is-- you're basically
indifferent whether you invest

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:26.390
the money in dollars,
or you go the way

00:08:26.390 --> 00:08:28.980
of exchanging into Euros, and
investing in Euros, and then

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:31.190
back into dollars.

00:08:31.190 --> 00:08:34.380
So in this example, the way
I've presented, worked it out,

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:35.309
there is no arbitrage.

00:08:35.309 --> 00:08:37.892
Now, if some of these numbers--
say the interest rate in Euros

00:08:37.892 --> 00:08:41.120
were 4% instead of 4.6, and
all the other quantities were

00:08:41.120 --> 00:08:44.750
the same, then, in fact,
there would be arbitrage.

00:08:44.750 --> 00:08:47.990
And you could make
money by borrowing money

00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:50.915
in dollars and investing.

00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:57.040
I mean, the purpose
of this slide

00:08:57.040 --> 00:08:59.160
is really to
illustrate kind of hey,

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:02.440
if there's no arbitrage,
how one would actually

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:04.280
compare-- how one
would actually look

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:07.140
for arbitrage in this example.

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:09.670
This is-- again, this is
a little bit of definition

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:13.505
what are compound
interest, interest rates.

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:19.366
We're going to talk about
instantaneous risk-free rates.

00:09:19.366 --> 00:09:21.240
We're going to, again,
say they're risk-free.

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:23.544
So basically, we
know for sure we're

00:09:23.544 --> 00:09:24.710
going to get our money back.

00:09:24.710 --> 00:09:27.340
You can think of
risk-free rates as the one

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:31.170
that treasuries pay in
real life, or the one

00:09:31.170 --> 00:09:33.490
that Federal Reserve
guarantees on deposits.

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:37.190
There's various examples
of risk-free rates.

00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:39.522
And while, in practice,
different risk-free rates

00:09:39.522 --> 00:09:41.980
can actually be different, so
they're not really risk-free.

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:45.482
But in our world right
now, in our model,

00:09:45.482 --> 00:09:46.940
we're going to
assume that there is

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:50.050
such a thing as a risk-free
rate for every currency,

00:09:50.050 --> 00:09:52.770
and it's unique.

00:09:52.770 --> 00:09:59.270
And now, as we talk about our
dynamics of the FX process,

00:09:59.270 --> 00:10:01.310
what's really focused
on here is an FX--

00:10:01.310 --> 00:10:03.380
we're making an FX model.

00:10:03.380 --> 00:10:05.870
And we want to see-- in
the previous example,

00:10:05.870 --> 00:10:09.525
we saw if you're given a FX rate
and given some interest rates,

00:10:09.525 --> 00:10:10.900
here's what the
FX forward really

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:14.270
has to be in order
to have no arbitrage.

00:10:14.270 --> 00:10:17.390
Well, now we are
trying to describe.

00:10:17.390 --> 00:10:20.905
We tried to describe or define
a process for the FX currency.

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:27.290
Essentially, this kind
of no-arbitrage condition

00:10:27.290 --> 00:10:33.060
leads to having
certain constraints

00:10:33.060 --> 00:10:35.470
on what the stochastic
differential

00:10:35.470 --> 00:10:36.870
equation has to be.

00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:39.600
So in this particular
case, the constraint

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:41.810
is that the drifts
of the process

00:10:41.810 --> 00:10:45.320
has to be the differential
in interest rates.

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:48.917
So if one currency pays more
than the other currency,

00:10:48.917 --> 00:10:51.250
obviously, people would want
to invest in that currency.

00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:54.070
So that in order for
no arbitrage to exist,

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:56.930
there has to be an expectation
that the currency that

00:10:56.930 --> 00:10:59.830
pays more would depreciate
in the future, otherwise

00:10:59.830 --> 00:11:03.000
it would be an arbitrage.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:06.080
So if it doesn't depreciate,
if you can kind of say,

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:08.740
hey, this currency
won't depreciate,

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:11.080
then you can just always
invest in that currency that

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:15.330
pays higher interest rates and
make money-- which, in fact,

00:11:15.330 --> 00:11:16.610
many people do.

00:11:16.610 --> 00:11:20.360
But again, that's a-- they're
taking a certain risk.

00:11:20.360 --> 00:11:24.290
They're taking the risk that
the currency will depreciate.

00:11:24.290 --> 00:11:26.700
So what do we actually want?

00:11:26.700 --> 00:11:32.460
What we want is to say--
we want to essentially--

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:35.500
and for the arbitrage
conditions from before-- which

00:11:35.500 --> 00:11:38.870
is to say that my forward rate
has to be essentially the spot

00:11:38.870 --> 00:11:46.660
rate-- well, this
condition here has

00:11:46.660 --> 00:11:48.750
to be observed, essentially.

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:50.780
And what does that mean?

00:11:50.780 --> 00:11:54.264
It means that my forward
rate has to be my spot--

00:11:54.264 --> 00:11:56.055
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
each other, you mean?

00:11:56.055 --> 00:11:56.530
STEFAN ANDREEV:
What did you say?

00:11:56.530 --> 00:11:57.480
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] set
those equal to each other?

00:11:57.480 --> 00:11:58.960
STEFAN ANDREEV: Yes.

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:04.900
My forward rate has to equal
to the spot rate times,

00:12:04.900 --> 00:12:08.251
essentially, the interest
rate differential.

00:12:08.251 --> 00:12:16.460
If that is true, than
in the previous set up,

00:12:16.460 --> 00:12:18.980
there will be no arbitrage.

00:12:18.980 --> 00:12:19.670
And why is that?

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:23.000
Well, that's because
the amount of money

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:27.825
I earn on the domestic
leg is e to the rd.

00:12:27.825 --> 00:12:31.730
The amount of money I earn on
the foreign leg is e to the rf,

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:35.030
but then I multiply
by the forward,

00:12:35.030 --> 00:12:39.490
and that has to equal
to the e to the rd.

00:12:39.490 --> 00:12:43.890
So this is a standard.

00:12:43.890 --> 00:12:49.040
This is a the most
basic dynamic FX model

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:51.180
that people use in industry.

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:54.930
It's referred to as the
Black-Scholes FX model.

00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:59.360
And the stock price-- you've
seen stochastic models before.

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:02.630
Usually, you see the stock price
when people talk about options.

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:10.470
In that case, this drift is just
the risk-free interest rate.

00:13:10.470 --> 00:13:14.710
Well, here in FX, it's a
differential of interest rates.

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:18.010
Otherwise, it's very similar.

00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:23.070
So FX has some
interesting properties.

00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:26.840
So we're gonna talk
about the game.

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:30.120
Before we go to the
game, one question:

00:13:30.120 --> 00:13:34.360
can FX exchange rate
ever be negative?

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:36.369
What do you guys think?

00:13:36.369 --> 00:13:38.285
Can the dollar-euro
exchange rate be negative?

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:44.980
Any ideas?

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:47.440
No, it's hard, because
what does negative mean?

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:52.970
It means I have to pay you
money to give you euros.

00:13:52.970 --> 00:13:54.251
Why would you?

00:13:54.251 --> 00:13:56.000
You have to pay me
money to give me euros.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.070
Nobody would do that.

00:13:57.070 --> 00:14:02.430
It can be 0, potentially,
if dollars are worthless

00:14:02.430 --> 00:14:05.740
or something, but it
cannot really be negative.

00:14:05.740 --> 00:14:13.150
So that's one reason why
I wrote my SDE as a kind

00:14:13.150 --> 00:14:14.270
of a log-normal process.

00:14:14.270 --> 00:14:18.010
You recognize this by
the form dS over S.

00:14:18.010 --> 00:14:22.480
So the changes in the FX are
proportional to the value

