00:20:58.045 --> 00:21:01.250
To give you an
illustration from finance,

00:21:01.250 --> 00:21:02.510
let's take Italy bonds.

00:21:02.510 --> 00:21:06.639
So Italy issues bonds both
in dollars and in euros.

00:21:06.639 --> 00:21:08.180
Why does it issue
in both currencies?

00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:10.460
Because Italy has to
issue a lot of bonds.

00:21:10.460 --> 00:21:15.270
And they need to find as
many investors as they can.

00:21:15.270 --> 00:21:17.220
And some investors
want to buy euro bonds,

00:21:17.220 --> 00:21:19.053
and some investors want
to buy dollar bonds.

00:21:19.053 --> 00:21:22.330
And they want to access
both bases of investors.

00:21:22.330 --> 00:21:25.810
Now, these bonds
they cross-default,

00:21:25.810 --> 00:21:29.900
meaning if Italy defaults on
one bond, all of its bonds

00:21:29.900 --> 00:21:34.880
default together, including
the euros and the dollar bonds.

00:21:34.880 --> 00:21:42.050
So then there is a
notion of credit spread,

00:21:42.050 --> 00:21:44.520
which is the measure
of how risky Italy is.

00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:46.260
So you can take
euro bonds, and you

00:21:46.260 --> 00:21:47.760
can say, well, how
much premium does

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:50.145
Italy pay over German bonds?

00:21:50.145 --> 00:21:52.020
Let's assume that German
bonds are risk-free,

00:21:52.020 --> 00:21:54.370
which is the standard
assumption for euros,

00:21:54.370 --> 00:22:00.270
that the German bonds--
Germany is the main underlying

00:22:00.270 --> 00:22:02.070
economic force for the Euro.

00:22:02.070 --> 00:22:04.770
They're kind of risk-free bonds.

00:22:04.770 --> 00:22:07.600
And Italy pays a certain
spread over euros.

00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:12.160
Same thing for dollars-- it
pays a certain spread over USA.

00:22:12.160 --> 00:22:13.650
So if Italy wants
to borrow money,

00:22:13.650 --> 00:22:15.220
they have to pay a
higher interest rate,

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:17.553
just like if you want to
borrow money for student loans,

00:22:17.553 --> 00:22:21.350
you have to pay higher
interest rate than the Fed.

00:22:21.350 --> 00:22:24.730
And the size of that
spread is in the market.

00:22:24.730 --> 00:22:29.240
It determines how risky
of a borrower you are.

00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:32.450
Well, it turns out that
these spreads are not

00:22:32.450 --> 00:22:34.130
the same in both currencies.

00:22:34.130 --> 00:22:37.981
One currency has a higher
spread than other currencies.

00:22:37.981 --> 00:22:39.480
That's kind of an
interesting thing.

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:42.510
So there is two
questions really:

00:22:42.510 --> 00:22:44.310
when the spreads
are not the same,

00:22:44.310 --> 00:22:47.880
which currency would Italy
prefer to issue bonds in?

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:51.047
And which currency do investors
prefer to buy bonds in?

00:22:54.530 --> 00:22:59.170
So this is kind of similar to
the previous game we played,

00:22:59.170 --> 00:23:03.330
because if you're an investor
trying to buy bonds, well,

00:23:03.330 --> 00:23:06.950
if Italy defaults,
then chances are

00:23:06.950 --> 00:23:09.830
the euro is not doing so well.

00:23:09.830 --> 00:23:12.030
So you would lose money.

00:23:12.030 --> 00:23:14.100
And if you have euro bonds,
you would lose euros.

00:23:14.100 --> 00:23:16.940
If you have dollar
bonds, you lose dollars.

00:23:16.940 --> 00:23:20.430
On the other hand, if Italy does
not default and pays you back,

00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:23.890
then chances are, euros
are not doing that bad.

00:23:23.890 --> 00:23:26.910
So you would actually be
making euros and dollars.

00:23:26.910 --> 00:23:29.810
So it's an
interesting-- it's kind

00:23:29.810 --> 00:23:32.090
